# ============================================================
# CityHealth — Capacitor APK Build Environment
# ============================================================
# Copy this file to .env.production.local on your local machine
# before running the Vite build for the Android APK.
# Replace the URL below with your deployed Replit app URL.
# ============================================================

# Full base URL for the API — must include /api at the end.
# When this variable is NOT set (local Vite dev), the app uses
# the Vite proxy and points to http://localhost:3001 automatically.
VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://YOUR_PROJECT.replit.app/api

# ============================================================
# Build steps (run these on your Windows machine)
# ============================================================
#
# 1. Install dependencies (only needed once):
#      npm install
#      npm install @capacitor/core @capacitor/cli @capacitor/android
#
# 2. Init Capacitor (only needed once):
#      npx cap init "CityHealth" "com.cityhealth.app" --web-dir dist
#
# 3. Add Android platform (only needed once):
#      npx cap add android
#
# 4. Build the Vite frontend pointing to your deployed backend.
#    Replace the URL with your real Replit app URL:
#
#    Windows PowerShell:
#      $env:VITE_API_BASE_URL="https://YOUR_PROJECT.replit.app/api"; npx vite build
#    Windows CMD:
#      set VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://YOUR_PROJECT.replit.app/api && npx vite build
#    Mac/Linux:
#      VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://YOUR_PROJECT.replit.app/api npx vite build
#
# 5. Copy built assets into the Android project:
#      npx cap sync android
#
# 6. Open in Android Studio to build/sign/export the APK:
#      npx cap open android
#    (Then: Build → Generate Signed Bundle / APK → APK)
#
# ============================================================
# Why VITE_API_BASE_URL is needed
# ============================================================
# In a Capacitor WebView the app is loaded from
# capacitor://localhost — a relative URL like /api/... would
# try to reach the device's local filesystem, not your server.
# Setting VITE_API_BASE_URL to your deployed backend URL makes
# every fetch go to the real API over HTTPS instead.
# ============================================================
